Video games are as much a consumer commodity as they are art. And you can make art in so many different ways, and you can make your art as accessible as possible. But it's never going to be possible to please everyone

And don't get me wrong, the anger is fine and valid and needs to be a part of this wider discussion, but treating it as though there are simple solutions with an industry this diverse and varied is not helpful.

This is why I'm defensive over games creating the experiences that they choose to create. This is why I argue subjectivity when it comes to accessibility. This is why I feel like this is a conversation with so much nuance that gets thrown to the wayside due to anger

I don't want my own art to be limited by what people think about it. I create my work so that if someone wants to try engaging in it, then they're allowed, but there are some experiences that we can't all have

Not every experience is meant to be for absolutely everyone. Not everyone is meant to be part of the audience. I don't want art to be something that's supposed to be considered universally acceptable. Fascism already tries to do that

-and therefore most "accessible" gameplay type out there. This is why I talk so much about subjectivity as far as difficulty modes go because I AM ACTUALLY USELESS AT THINGS THAT ARE MEANT TO BE SIMPLE

I cannot play horror games. Full stop, they are not for me because I have anxiety and do not like being scared. But that is my problem, which is why I do not play horror games. I also cannot play literally any point-and-click despite them being potentially the "easiest"+

Horror games! You wouldn't decry a horror game for being scary or for having potentially disturbing content! And no one ever brings them up in this sorta discussion because you wouldn't tell a horror game to stop being scary to make people more comfortable

There are games I enjoy that I know some folks cannot play due to them being in the first person, causing motion sickness. First person games are designed to be in the first person, and changing the perspective would be antithetical to the design ethos of those games.

-in comparison to how outwardly punishing the previous titles have been. It is arguably for more accessible despite the singular gameplay mode. But accessible does not necessarily mean that it's for everyone.

-like what makes the game "inaccessible" because while it is not perfect and is still very much in the same vein as other Fromsoft titles, it is far and above the most user friendly game that they have made, from how weapons function to the number of places to rest+

The original point I started this thread was sparked when I saw someone asking if Eld*n Ring has an easy mode, which the very obvious answer is that the game just has the one mode of play. But based on everything that I've heard and read about the game, that doesn't seem+

This is why if I'm playing a game that does not give me a goal to achieve, I will inevitably find myself incredibly lost and the likelihood that I'm going to continue playing it starts to fall lower and lower

For me accessibility looks like animations that I can easily read to anticipate what is coming next; having subtitles to deal with auditory processing; the ability to adjust my keybinds to my own personal comfort; very clear and direct questmarkers and tutorial modes.

There are things that can be done to make the game potentially playable by the greatest number of people possible but you can still have all of that and what makes something perceived as "easy" will still be incredibly variable

-to the player on the other side of the screen. Being able to remap controls and clearly signaling combat moves, having trigger warnings, adjusting colors, allowing for save states, having subtitles or not having them, adjusting motion blur, tutorials, the list goes on and on.

Accessibility is about providing the tools that will allow people to play a game but no game can provide a universally approachable system that works for everyone. You can provide the things that make a game playable but where that goes from there is entirely subjective+

There are a ton of games I've played with an Easy difficulty that I find almost impossible to play. That doesn't mean that they're inherently inaccessible, it means that the gameplay mode is not for me and that is okay

Story based point-and-clicks. Managerial/simple task based games. Things that I personally find incredibly difficult due to a combination of ADHD and other factors. I get very overwhelmed by task logs, I get very easily distracted. Too much choice or open ends can be a hindrance

Continuing my train of thought while I ignore my friends jumping down my throat, you can do a lot of things that make it easier to play a game but equating easy with accessible shouldn't be the discussion. You know what games are supposedly very easy?

@fluidfyre I really hope you're just venting and not positing that that's how I feel about the matter... because it's not, but there's a lotta different factors to accessibility and game types. Even "easy" games will prevent people, like myself, from being able to play them
@fluidfyre Like I'm not saying that there isn't ableism involved in a lot of it, but it's more the debate of what makes something an "easy" mode because that kinda thing is really subjective

I keep thinking about the 'accessibility' of games and  how obnoxious it is to insist that a game do something that it's not meant to do. Like, for Soulslike games, the challenge is the point. It feels like looking at an FPS and going "hm no you need to make it 3rd person for me"

Living life with neurodivergence is not easy but neither is the harm that comes from trying to make myself 'fit' with neurotypicals

-my symptoms' being so much louder. I stim way more, I'm more interruptive (which I'm so sorry D&D group), my emotions are bigger. But I'm happier because instead of masking, I'm making it work and learning ways to adapt that don't hamper my brain's needs

For most of my life growing up, I was depersonalized as a result of masking (and some trauma but that's just part of it all). In the last few years since coming into my own as an adult, I've been masking less and less and my headspace is so much healthier despite +

-that none of it ~really~ mattered. We're pushing two years of living in a global health crisis with a death toll only growing while we're lied to about how the danger is over when it's really not. Now we're stuck in the anger part of healing

Since the pandemic hit, it feels like it's all just gotten so much worse. Community is no longer safe, and almost everyone is hurting in some way. For over a year we were forced into isolation with our own grief and the pain it brings, and now the people in charge have decided+
-of what trauma does to us

There's such a stigma, or maybe it's a taboo, against expressing your grief publicly. Mourning is meant to be something that we go through with community, funerals used to be about coming together but even they were A Single Event that doesn't take into account the reality +
-"You're allowed to be hurt, and you're allowed to fall back into pain, you're allowed to take the time that you need in order to recover and find your version of normalcy"

It takes a lot to find proper support structures when everything else is demanding that you Be Better, Right Now, Or Else. Even when I try to give myself the space I need and make myself a harbor for my friends going through it, it feels like rebellion to say +
Healing isn't linear but our society, from work to even interpersonal relationships, winds up reinforcing a demand to get back to ~normal~ and whatever that might be interpreted as

So much of the pandemic has been about various types of grief and the trauma of that, I think, is going to haunt a lot of us for years because there are no real support systems. I lost a best friend in December of 2020 and I *still* get hit with grief triggers

Most times it feels like we're so expected to be able to move on and get back to work that all of our strong emotions are dismissed outright, or given a "damn that sucks" acknowledgement before it becomes too awkward and you have to push it aside to avoid being bothersome https://t.co/O9RqtzdXlU

I'm at a point where, if my writing isn't pushing development forward, then I don't wanna write it

One of my chapters might be 3000 words long. Another might be 600. To me, if they're pushing the narrative forward, then they're doing their job. Filler can be fine and all but tbh it just turns my prose into mush

Especially when it comes to the environment of posting fanworks on AO3, there's a bit of pressure to produce lengthy chapters to draw readers in with the promise of an investment. But I've come to find that needlessly extending prose is really unhelpful
I think that one of the things that's allowed me to grow the most as a writer when it comes to long form works is that, chapters don't have to be any longer than they need to be
